00:15:11.830 --> 00:15:14.690
But to make this plate,
he went down the street

00:15:14.690 --> 00:15:19.790
to a metal working lighting shop
called Cornelius and Company,

00:15:19.790 --> 00:15:23.010
where he requested silver
coated copper plates.

00:15:23.010 --> 00:15:27.050 position:56%
And that man who made his silver
coated copper plates was a man named

00:15:27.050 --> 00:15:28.760
Robert Cornelius.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:34.450
So, Robert Cornelius, and this
is a later photograph of him,

00:15:34.450 --> 00:15:37.600
not only was a metal worker
but he had an interest

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:39.970
and a background in chemistry.

00:15:39.970 --> 00:15:42.100
When learning of Saxton's
experimentation

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:48.640
with the daguerreotype, he
too, decided to give it a try.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:51.010
So, Cornelius set up
his daguerreotype camera

00:15:51.010 --> 00:15:55.220
in the back alley of his
family's company shop

00:15:55.220 --> 00:15:59.790 position:56%
and he placed is sensitized plate
and the camera and he stood in front

00:15:59.790 --> 00:16:04.030
of the camera lens for quite a long
time to take what we know today

00:16:04.030 --> 00:16:08.730
to be the very first self portrait.

00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:11.450 position:56%
So, some of the facts you should
know about the daguerreotype process

00:16:11.450 --> 00:16:15.450
in 1839, as I mentioned, the
exposure times were quite long.

00:16:15.450 --> 00:16:18.740
So, they could range anywhere from
three to 15 minutes and upwards

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:22.040
to half an hour depending on
the light conditions outside

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.640
and the brightness of the sun.

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:27.850
The long exposures prohibited
the capturing of motion.

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:34.140
So, if you see most of the early
1839 daguerreotypes are landscapes

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:37.680
and then if you look at them,
you won't see any people on them.

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:40.760
So, Daguerre took a lot
of street scenes of Paris

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:44.340
and there aren't any people in
most of those daguerreotypes.

00:16:44.340 --> 00:16:47.820
And the reason for this is that
because the exposure time could be

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:51.450
up to half an hour, if anybody was
just walking by on the streets,

00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:53.510
they wouldn't get captured
in the image.

00:16:53.510 --> 00:16:56.360
You'd have to stand still
in the frame of the camera

00:16:56.360 --> 00:17:00.780
for a significant amount of
time to procure a daguerreotype.

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:03.450
So, a lot of people thought that
Daguerre woke up really early

00:17:03.450 --> 00:17:06.130
in the morning when the
streets weren't busy

00:17:06.130 --> 00:17:08.270
and took these photographs,
but actually,

00:17:08.270 --> 00:17:09.810
it's just the long exposure time

00:17:09.810 --> 00:17:12.940
that prohibits the
motion being captured.

00:17:15.070 --> 00:17:21.130
So, Robert Cornelius, after
he made his self portrait,

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:24.210
he decides to collaborate
with another chemist

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:26.110 position:56%
from the University of Pennsylvania.

00:17:26.110 --> 00:17:27.740
And if you've been to Philadelphia,

00:17:27.740 --> 00:17:31.390
you know Philadelphia Center City
is quite small and compact and all

00:17:31.390 --> 00:17:33.990
of these places were located sort

00:17:33.990 --> 00:17:36.740
of within a block or
two of one another.

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:39.240
So, here's University of
Pennsylvania, US Mint,

00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:43.970
Cornelius's family business,
the Franklin Institute,

00:17:43.970 --> 00:17:46.240
the American Philosophical
Science Society.

00:17:46.240 --> 00:17:49.530 position:56%
And all these places I'm going to be
talking about are within, you know,

00:17:49.530 --> 00:17:51.650
five minutes walk of one another.

00:17:51.650 --> 00:17:54.060
So, at the University
of Pennsylvania,

00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:59.110
there was a man named Paul Beck
Goddard and he was a chemist

00:17:59.110 --> 00:18:01.440
and he had an interest
in making daguerreotypes.

00:18:01.440 --> 00:18:05.840 position:56%
And on the right here is a
landscape daguerreotype that he made

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:10.310 position:56%
from his window at the University of
Pennsylvania in 1839 and it belongs

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:12.610
to the Franklin Institute.

00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:17.830
So because Cornelius had taken
the self portrait using the

00:18:17.830 --> 00:18:21.240
daguerreotype process which as I
mentioned had a very long exposure

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:24.710
time, the two men saw
this marketability

00:18:24.710 --> 00:18:27.610
and the daguerreotype
for portraiture.

00:18:27.610 --> 00:18:30.140
However, because the
exposures were so long,

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:32.240
it really made this
process unsuitable

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:35.590
for rendering the likeness
of a human image.

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:37.590
As the sitter would have
to sit perfectly still

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:41.370
for a very long time, which
try to sit in your seat

00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:44.930
for the next two minutes and
not move, it's really difficult.

00:18:44.930 --> 00:18:47.520
So, together, they experimented

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:51.680
with the sensitization
step of the process.

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:56.190
And in order to reduce the
exposure time of the plate,

00:18:56.190 --> 00:19:00.030
they replaced one halogen, which
in Daguerre's original formula was

00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:02.210
iodine with bromine.

00:19:02.210 --> 00:19:04.460
And first experiment show

00:19:04.460 --> 00:19:06.740
that bromine had a little
bit of hazing on the plate.

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:10.170
So, they were doing some
experiment with iodine

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:12.680
and bromine and then iodine again.

00:19:12.680 --> 00:19:16.320
But with these experiments
and changing out the halogen,

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:20.180 position:56%
they were able to make the exposure
time of the plate, they could cut it

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:23.400
in half, which made still
a long time to sit still

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:28.440
but way less excruciating
than, you know, 15 minutes.

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:33.140
So, just a little side
note of interest, bromine,

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:38.060
the element wasn't even discovered
until 1826 and we're talking

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:41.840
about 1839 right now, so, this
is just a little over 10 years

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:44.560
after this element
is even discovered.

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:49.760 position:56%
And legend has it that Cornelius and
Goddard bought up all the bromine

00:19:49.760 --> 00:19:52.510
that they could possibly
get in the area.

00:19:52.510 --> 00:19:54.350
So, the philosophical
society in Philadelphia

00:19:54.350 --> 00:19:57.340
and the Franklin Institute
were the main two places

00:19:57.340 --> 00:20:02.050
where you would present
new scientific discoveries.

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:06.970
So, Cornelius and Goddard presented
these two particular daguerreotypes

00:20:06.970 --> 00:20:09.860 position:56%
there at one of the annual meetings.

00:20:09.860 --> 00:20:13.770
And the one on the left
the portrait of Goddard.

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:18.040
So, this one was made before
Cornelius's studio opened,

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:21.180
but it would make sense that
you would take a picture

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:22.520
of your partner.

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:27.300
So, in 1840, these were
presented with great praise

00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:31.570 position:56%
at the American Philosophical
Society to the scientific community.

00:20:33.790 --> 00:20:38.490
So, Cornelius went on for the
next year making portraits

00:20:38.490 --> 00:20:41.320
in his first studio at
8th and Lodge Alley.

00:20:41.320 --> 00:20:44.610
So, if you're familiar
with Philadelphia, it's--

00:20:44.610 --> 00:20:46.820
8th between Chestnut and Market.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:49.640
And Lodge Alley no longer exists.

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:54.080
All of these images were made
on plates that Cornelius made

00:20:54.080 --> 00:20:55.510
since he was a metal worker.

00:20:55.510 --> 00:20:57.260
And all of these image are housed

00:20:57.260 --> 00:20:59.860
in a very non-traditional
metal frame style

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:01.890
that Cornelius made himself.

00:21:01.890 --> 00:21:05.860
And these three examples are
some of the variants you will see

00:21:05.860 --> 00:21:10.120
from his handmade housing samples.

00:21:12.500 --> 00:21:16.180
Additionally, on the verse of all
of the Cornelius daguerreotypes,

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:19.010
you will see a paper backing
that contains a paper label

00:21:19.010 --> 00:21:21.510
with the Cornelius studio name.

00:21:21.510 --> 00:21:23.290
So, this was sort of the way

00:21:23.290 --> 00:21:26.420
that an artist would sign
his painting, daguerreotype.

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:29.660
This is the way to sign
your daguerreotype.

00:21:29.660 --> 00:21:35.120
So, the following year in 1841,

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:38.270
Cornelius set up a
second portrait studio.

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:42.290
And this one was on a second floor
and it had better natural lighting.

00:21:42.290 --> 00:21:45.750
And at this point, Cornelius had
really kind of perfected his craft

00:21:45.750 --> 00:21:49.740
of portraiture in the short time
that he was making daguerreotypes.

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:53.320
And he was able to reflect the sun
from his window on to his sitters

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:58.120
in a way that made it much
more painterly and scholarly.

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:01.660
And with this area or
portraiture, he also put his images

00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:05.520
into traditional leather cases
that we use here in America.

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:11.590
So, daguerreotypes in Paris
were put into his glass housing

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:15.690
that were called passepartout that
contain the reversed painted glass.

00:22:15.690 --> 00:22:20.310
But in America, we traditionally
used little leather-embossed cases.

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:26.160
But while you can't see the
Cornelius paper label on these,

00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:29.410
he did emboss his brass
mass with his name

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:31.610
and his studio address on them.

00:22:31.610 --> 00:22:34.660
So, you'll know which
ones are Cornelius's.

00:22:39.790 --> 00:22:43.210
Cornelius also-- He
retired in-- from--

00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:47.250
he had a studio from
1840, he closed in 1843.

00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:52.310
There's not a lot of records left
behind or notes from his studio.

00:22:52.310 --> 00:22:57.490
There aren't list of people
he took his-- were sitters.

00:22:57.490 --> 00:23:01.160
So, all that's left there are
the artifacts of his labor.

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:04.110
So we know that Cornelius's
family was

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:05.410
in the laying [phonetic] business

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:08.160
and the gas plants were coming
very popular at this time.

00:23:08.160 --> 00:23:12.270
So, whether he went back to
work in his family's company

00:23:12.270 --> 00:23:16.220
out of necessity or he just grew
tired of making daguerreotypes,

00:23:16.220 --> 00:23:18.190
I'm not really sure of the later.

00:23:18.190 --> 00:23:21.040
It seems feasible but
this is what you will read

00:23:21.040 --> 00:23:23.140
in the historic literature.

00:23:23.140 --> 00:23:28.500
But he closed off his shop in
1843 and he did make a handful

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:35.570
of daguerreotypes post his
"retirement" up until 1847.

00:23:35.570 --> 00:23:44.970
So, as I mentioned, he didn't
leave behind any logbooks,

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:48.100
we don't have records
of his studio but his--

00:23:48.100 --> 00:23:51.070
the portraits that he left behind
are really quite remarkable.

00:23:51.070 --> 00:23:57.360
And his first studio portraits
were very straight on,

00:23:57.360 --> 00:24:01.150
straightforward images
and bust from the waist up

00:24:01.150 --> 00:24:04.200
and they were very
nice and very skilled.

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:06.830
But by the time he made
it to his second studio,

00:24:06.830 --> 00:24:11.450
I think he really perfected
his angles of his sitters

00:24:11.450 --> 00:24:14.290
and his portraits became
pretty phenomenal.

00:24:14.290 --> 00:24:18.460
And on the-- This is a comparison,
on the left is the first studio

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:21.450
and the right is the second studio.

00:24:21.450 --> 00:24:23.090
And it's not just me thing

00:24:23.090 --> 00:24:28.040
that I think Robert Cornelius's
portraits were pretty great,

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:31.260
Daguerre himself found
Cornelius's portraits

00:24:31.260 --> 00:24:33.190
to be pretty phenomenal as well.

00:24:33.190 --> 00:24:38.700
So, and he-- Daguerre sent
a mammoth-like daguerreotype

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:44.440
of Notre Dame to the Franklin
Institute in this note on the back

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:47.070
of the daguerreotype indicates

00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:52.570
that Daguerre was sending this
particular daguerreotype to America

00:24:52.570 --> 00:24:56.480
in exchange for portraits
made by Robert Cornelius.

00:24:56.480 --> 00:24:58.520
So, to have the inventor

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:02.930
of the process request your
daguerreotype is probably the

00:25:02.930 --> 00:25:08.950
highest honor you could have.

00:25:08.950 --> 00:25:10.600
However, all that remains
in the legend

00:25:10.600 --> 00:25:13.690
of Robert Cornelius can only
be deduced in the series

00:25:13.690 --> 00:25:18.450
of beautiful portraits he
captured between 1839 and 1847,

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:22.180
in the earliest era of
photography in the United States.

00:25:22.180 --> 00:25:27.260
And as of now, there
are fewer than 50

00:25:27.260 --> 00:25:31.280
of his daguerreotypes
known to have survived.

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:34.540
And these are just
some of the locations

00:25:34.540 --> 00:25:37.740
that hold Cornelius's
daguerreotypes.

00:25:40.190 --> 00:25:42.610
So, for those who don't know
what a daguerreotype is,

00:25:42.610 --> 00:25:45.790
I will give you a little
explanation.

00:25:45.790 --> 00:25:48.480
So, it's a highly polished
silver plate,

00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:52.580
it's most commonly a thin layer
of silver coated over copper

00:25:52.580 --> 00:25:55.540
that has been smoothed
to a mirror finish.

00:25:55.540 --> 00:26:02.490
And the process of making a
daguerreotype goes as follows.

00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:06.560
Step number one is to prepare
your silver coated copper plate

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:08.310
by clipping the corners.

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:11.530
This helps you with polishing.

00:26:11.530 --> 00:26:13.700
And the second step is to
polish your silver plate

00:26:13.700 --> 00:26:15.660
to a mirror finish.

00:26:15.660 --> 00:26:18.960
This polishing takes
many, many hours to do

00:26:18.960 --> 00:26:23.490
to get the daguerreotype
smooth and shiny.

00:26:23.490 --> 00:26:26.330
And you will often see when you
look at a daguerreotype and hold it

00:26:26.330 --> 00:26:29.980
on a certain angle that you can see
the polished marks and you can tell

00:26:29.980 --> 00:26:35.070
which direction they go,
up or down or side to side.

00:26:35.070 --> 00:26:38.670
Number three is to subject the
plate to vapors of halogen.

00:26:38.670 --> 00:26:43.200 position:56%
And as I mentioned before Daguerre's
original formula used iodine

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:47.160 position:56%
and then later, it's what we call
double sensitization, so it's iodine

00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:50.860
and bromine or a combination
of the two.

00:26:50.860 --> 00:26:53.270
And that made the plate
light sensitive.

00:26:53.270 --> 00:26:56.190
At that point, you would place your
plate in the daguerreotype camera

00:26:56.190 --> 00:26:59.190
to take the exposure
and after that was done,

00:26:59.190 --> 00:27:02.890
you would develop your images
in the fumes or mercury.

00:27:02.890 --> 00:27:06.050
And to stop that silver
reaction, this is where that fixer

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:09.160
or sodium thiosulfate comes in.

00:27:09.160 --> 00:27:14.040
And then, the next step in
this timeline occurs post 1841

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:17.000
and doesn't apply to the
earliest daguerreotypes

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.040
but there was a step called gilding

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:23.200
and this was the coating
of gold chloride.

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:27.350
And the gold chloride would be
put on the surface of the plate,

00:27:27.350 --> 00:27:31.160
and I'll explain this a little
bit more in detail later

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:36.050 position:56%
but in the earliest of
Cornelius's experiments, this step--

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:38.430
sorry, step did not exist.

00:27:38.430 --> 00:27:41.810
And then the final step for all
daguerreotypes was to seal them

00:27:41.810 --> 00:27:46.470
up because this is a highly
polished piece of silver

00:27:46.470 --> 00:27:48.100
and it tarnished quite readily.

00:27:48.100 --> 00:27:51.760
So, they've figured out pretty
quickly that they needed to seal it

00:27:51.760 --> 00:27:53.150
in some sort of environment

00:27:53.150 --> 00:27:55.960
that would protect it
from the atmosphere.

00:28:01.070 --> 00:28:02.930
So, this is what the
finished product

00:28:02.930 --> 00:28:05.130
of a daguerreotype looks like.

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:07.810
And it's a little bit hard
to see when you pick one

00:28:07.810 --> 00:28:10.610
up because it's a mirror
and it's reflective.

00:28:10.610 --> 00:28:15.440
So, at a certain angle, with a dark
material blocking the reflectance,

00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:17.360
you can actually see
the daguerreotype image.

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:19.590
So, you could see the woman here.

00:28:19.590 --> 00:28:23.490
And if you tilt it a little
bit, the image become--

00:28:23.490 --> 00:28:25.770
appears more like a negative.

00:28:25.770 --> 00:28:29.650
So, the silver changes
and it makes the parts

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:32.850
that stick out sort of recess.

00:28:32.850 --> 00:28:37.220
And if you tilt it even more,
it just becomes a solid mirror.

00:28:37.220 --> 00:28:40.600
So, you can see the reflectance
of this newspaper in the image.

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:48.290
So, as I mentioned before
daguerreotypes needed to be sealed

00:28:48.290 --> 00:28:53.020
to slow down the sulfur and other
pollutants in the atmosphere to--

00:28:53.020 --> 00:28:55.730
from tarnishing the silver plate.

00:28:55.730 --> 00:28:58.680
And I mentioned that the French
used the reverse painted glass

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:03.250
passepartout and in America, we
use these embossed leather cases

00:29:03.250 --> 00:29:05.600
that were made into standard sizes.

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:11.170 position:56%
So, the daguerreotype package would
generally include Daguerre brass mat

00:29:11.170 --> 00:29:14.680
that was placed directly on
top of the daguerreotype plate.

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:18.480 position:56%
Over that, a shade of glass would be
put on top and around the perimeter

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:20.930
of this package, it was usually
sealed off with some kind

00:29:20.930 --> 00:29:22.680
of paper tape with an adhesive.

00:29:22.680 --> 00:29:27.540
And then, that tape would be
covered by a brass preserver

00:29:27.540 --> 00:29:32.490
to cover the seal around
the daguerreotype package.

00:29:32.490 --> 00:29:35.700
And the entire daguerreotype
package will be fitted into one

00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:38.500
of these custom leather
cases and the leather,

00:29:38.500 --> 00:29:43.800
it was usually embossed leather
and there was on the lid side,

00:29:43.800 --> 00:29:46.770
there's a material that
help with the reflectance

00:29:46.770 --> 00:29:48.440
and viewing of the daguerreotype.

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:52.020
So, in this particular one I have
on the screen, it's a solid piece

00:29:52.020 --> 00:29:54.590
of silk and that's sort of
the earlier style of case

00:29:54.590 --> 00:29:58.670
but later they became dark
colored embossed velvet.

00:30:02.820 --> 00:30:04.800
So, in addition of
providing the daguerreotype

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:10.840
with a special handheld housing,
the cases and passepartout served

00:30:10.840 --> 00:30:14.990
as protection from the harmful
gases in the environment.

00:30:14.990 --> 00:30:18.410
Being pure of silver, the
plates had a tendency to tarnish

00:30:18.410 --> 00:30:20.700
if they were left bare
and open to the elements.

00:30:20.700 --> 00:30:24.530
So, on the left is an example
where the tarnish is quite heavy

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:28.400
and the pattern that forms
corresponds to the shape usually

00:30:28.400 --> 00:30:31.580
of the brass mat that
sat on top of it.

00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:35.550 position:56%
Color interference rings would cover
the surface obscuring the image

00:30:35.550 --> 00:30:37.850
from the outside in.

00:30:37.850 --> 00:30:41.520
Daguerreotypes are also susceptible
to abrasion and that layer

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:44.990
of silver that's coated on
the copper is extremely thin.

00:30:44.990 --> 00:30:48.400
So, if you touched it with your
finger or some other material,

00:30:48.400 --> 00:30:50.650
you could easily disrupt the silver

00:30:50.650 --> 00:30:53.300
and the copper beneath
could be exposed.

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:56.050
And if you have moisture
in the environment,

00:30:56.050 --> 00:30:59.290
then copper corrosion can form
and little mushroom like areas

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:03.410
of copper byproducts can protrude
to the surface of the daguerreotype

00:31:03.410 --> 00:31:06.190
and you can see that
in the daguerreotype

00:31:06.190 --> 00:31:08.610
on the right, the sitter
on the left.

00:31:09.830 --> 00:31:11.130
One other common problem

00:31:11.130 --> 00:31:14.070
that daguerreotypes have are
deterioration over time is

00:31:14.070 --> 00:31:17.800
that the glass that's placed
on top of them also corrodes.

00:31:17.800 --> 00:31:20.970
And the glass will ooze out
silica and other byproducts

00:31:20.970 --> 00:31:24.840
of the glass production and
so it's the lag type forms--

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:27.350
formations that dangle
down from the glass

00:31:27.350 --> 00:31:31.220
on to the copper-- the
daguerreotype plate.

00:31:34.410 --> 00:31:36.830
So, the oldest of the
daguerreotypes--

00:31:36.830 --> 00:31:39.400
daguerreotype plates
are at the greatest risk

00:31:39.400 --> 00:31:42.640
to these naturally occurring
deterioration issues.

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:43.940
And this is the rubber

00:31:43.940 --> 00:31:47.780
in Cornelius's self portrait that's
owned by the Library of Congress.

00:31:47.780 --> 00:31:50.640
And you can see on the
right, in this detail

00:31:50.640 --> 00:31:55.110
that the perimeter
tarnishing is quite heavy.

00:31:58.510 --> 00:32:03.600
And these two Cornelius plates
that is shown before exhibit,

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:06.030 position:56%
a white haze around their perimeters

00:32:06.030 --> 00:32:09.840
and these are the byproducts
of historic cleaning.

00:32:09.840 --> 00:32:11.340
These two daguerreotypes are owned

00:32:11.340 --> 00:32:15.690
by the American Philosophical
Society and they were brought to me

00:32:15.690 --> 00:32:17.680
at the conservation center

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:21.020
by Philosophical Society's
conserver Anne Downey.

00:32:21.020 --> 00:32:26.200
And Anne was concerned that when
she began working at her job

00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:30.190
that she had seen these and then
she'd look at them really recently

00:32:30.190 --> 00:32:35.330 position:56%
and she thought they had changed and
had more tarnished and more hazing

00:32:35.330 --> 00:32:38.440
than she remembered when
she started at her job.

00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:42.830
And she asked me if there was
anything I could do to treat them.

00:32:42.830 --> 00:32:47.140
And I knew they're Robert Cornelius
daguerreotypes and looking at them

00:32:47.140 --> 00:32:50.070
that they were some of the earliest
daguerreotypes made here in America

00:32:50.070 --> 00:32:53.660
and I told her there was no
way I can just do a treatment

00:32:53.660 --> 00:32:55.780
on these two daguerreotypes.

00:32:55.780 --> 00:32:58.560
There has to be a huge
research project.

00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:02.470
We don't have a lot of information
about these early materials.

00:33:02.470 --> 00:33:08.060
So, my first step was to telephone
my colleague Adrienne Lundgren here

00:33:08.060 --> 00:33:11.900 position:56%
at the Library of Congress because I
know she really loves daguerreotypes

00:33:11.900 --> 00:33:15.330
as much as I do and I also knew
that there was a large collection

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:19.380 position:56%
of Robert Cornelius's holdings here.

00:33:19.380 --> 00:33:23.900
So, together we talked about,
you know, I explained my problem

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:27.120
and she was telling me that she had
the self portrait and it was not

00:33:27.120 --> 00:33:28.420
in very good shape either.

00:33:28.420 --> 00:33:33.270 position:56%
So, together we decided we needed to
collaborate on a research project.

00:33:34.830 --> 00:33:39.840
So, several issues that post
challenges for conservators

00:33:39.840 --> 00:33:43.040
with these materials, their--

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:46.120
the primary issue is that the
daguerreotypes that were made

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:50.240
between 1839 and 1841
were not gilded,

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:53.480
and I mentioned this gold
chloride stuff in the production

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:55.440
of the daguerreotype earlier.

00:33:55.440 --> 00:34:00.540 position:56%
So, the gilding added a protective
layer to the silver image particles,

00:34:00.540 --> 00:34:04.910
it also helped make the image a
little more adorable and stable

00:34:04.910 --> 00:34:06.910
than their ungilded counterparts.

00:34:06.910 --> 00:34:10.070
The gilding also helped
visually with some

00:34:10.070 --> 00:34:12.960
of the contrast of the image.

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:17.530
So, when you compare ungilded n
the left versus the gilded image

00:34:17.530 --> 00:34:20.540
on the right, you can see the
ungilded image is a little

00:34:20.540 --> 00:34:22.850
bit flatter.

00:34:22.850 --> 00:34:28.740
But both images, all daguerreotypes
are incredibly fragile materials,

00:34:28.740 --> 00:34:33.550
it just happens that the ungilded
daguerreotype are even more prone

00:34:33.550 --> 00:34:35.270
to abrasion, which limits a lot

00:34:35.270 --> 00:34:39.460 position:56%
of the treatment options we have
currently for gilded daguerreotypes,

00:34:39.460 --> 00:34:42.360
which comprises most of
the body of daguerreotypes.

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:49.450
So, the tarnishing of the
silver is the second issue

00:34:49.450 --> 00:34:51.160
that we need to consider.

00:34:51.160 --> 00:34:53.760
So, tarnish was a problem from
the beginning of production

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:56.760
of daguerreotypes as I
mentioned and so much

00:34:56.760 --> 00:34:59.860
so by 1850 it was very common

00:34:59.860 --> 00:35:02.890
that tarnishes already occurred
on daguerreotype plates.

00:35:02.890 --> 00:35:07.560
And people in the 19th century
were cleaning daguerreotypes

00:35:07.560 --> 00:35:10.990
with solution of potassium cyanide.

00:35:10.990 --> 00:35:13.960
So with this cleaner, it
might work miracles at time--

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:17.960
at that time and it might have made
the plate pretty shiny and new.

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:26.630
But today, 177 years later residual
amounts of cyanide can be found

00:35:26.630 --> 00:35:29.930
on the surfaces of
daguerreotype plate.

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:35.740
And you can see deterioration
that was caused by the cyanide.

00:35:35.740 --> 00:35:37.190
So, cyanide can be found

00:35:37.190 --> 00:35:39.420
on the daguerreotype
plate for many reasons.

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:43.020
Sometimes, it was used in the
production of the plate cladding.

00:35:43.020 --> 00:35:45.620
Sometimes it was used
in the development.

00:35:45.620 --> 00:35:50.200
And sometimes, it could just be
caused from historic cleaning.

00:35:50.200 --> 00:35:52.530
In this side-by-side
comparison on the left,

00:35:52.530 --> 00:35:55.780
you can see the corresponding
tarnish on the silver plate

00:35:55.780 --> 00:35:59.210
with the pattern of the fluorescent
cyanide in the image next to it.

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:03.940
So, the image on the right is an
image under ultraviolet light,

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:09.240
under UVC and it shows all of that
fluorescence caused by the cyanide.

00:36:09.240 --> 00:36:11.580
You can't see that
with the visible eye.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:14.330
But you can look in the bottom
right corner and see sort

00:36:14.330 --> 00:36:17.510
of a corresponding
pattern of deterioration

00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:22.570
and that is pretty aligned
with the cyanide on the plate.

00:36:22.570 --> 00:36:29.970
And then later in the 20th century,
in the 1950s we had a new compound

00:36:29.970 --> 00:36:32.660 position:56%
for clearing silver called thiourea.

00:36:32.660 --> 00:36:36.430
And thiourea started to be
used to clean daguerreotypes.

00:36:36.430 --> 00:36:40.080 position:56%
And again, this was another compound

00:36:40.080 --> 00:36:43.370
that you'd clean your daguerreotype
with, probably looked pretty great

00:36:43.370 --> 00:36:49.140
at the time, but now, you know, 40,
50 years later, we are seeing a lot

00:36:49.140 --> 00:36:53.080
of white residues and hazing on
daguerreotypes that were cleaned

00:36:53.080 --> 00:36:56.640
with thiourea and likely
not washed very well

00:36:56.640 --> 00:36:59.340
or over cleaned with thiourea.

00:36:59.340 --> 00:37:03.550
And cleaning of daguerreotypes
with this solution was very popular

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:07.020
so much so that it was published
in a Time Life book series,

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:09.710
it was in many photographic
magazines.

00:37:09.710 --> 00:37:12.810
So, a lot of people were
cleaning their daguerreotypes

00:37:12.810 --> 00:37:17.680
and not necessarily conservators
or scientists, people just--

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:19.420
who had daguerreotypes read

00:37:19.420 --> 00:37:22.770
about this new cleaning method
and we're trying it out.

00:37:22.770 --> 00:37:26.780
So, this will play a big
part a little bit later

00:37:26.780 --> 00:37:29.760
on what we're dealing with
today as conservators.

00:37:29.760 --> 00:37:34.670
So just to give you an idea,
this is the daguerreotypes

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:37.900
of Paul Beck Goddard that APS has.

00:37:37.900 --> 00:37:42.340
And this one was cleaned in
thiourea in the late 1970s.

00:37:42.340 --> 00:37:44.890
And I know this for a fact
because there's a note on the back

00:37:44.890 --> 00:37:47.920 position:56%
of this daguerreotype indicating so.

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:52.260
So, well, I'm sure it looked pretty
good at the time it was cleaned.

00:37:52.260 --> 00:37:54.920
Now, it doesn't look
so great 40 years later

00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:59.510
and you could see there's a
white haze around the perimeter

00:37:59.510 --> 00:38:02.570
so that area would have been
the heaviest area of tarnish.

00:38:02.570 --> 00:38:08.690
So that thiourea has left a
really undesirable white hazing

00:38:08.690 --> 00:38:13.350
on the heaviest part of the silver,
but there's also a haze overall.

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:18.510
And then another result of these
historic cleanings is what we

00:38:18.510 --> 00:38:19.810
call measles.

00:38:19.810 --> 00:38:22.230
So, on the right if
you look at that image,

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:25.780
same image in specular
illumination and you can see all

00:38:25.780 --> 00:38:28.860
of these brown tiny dots
on the surface of the plate

00:38:28.860 --> 00:38:34.320 position:56%
and those are all residual
byproducts of the historic cleaning.

00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:39.010
And here's the detail
under the microscope.

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:42.160
You can see, this is the surface
of the plate and there are a bunch

00:38:42.160 --> 00:38:43.920
of abrasions and scratches.

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:47.800
And I'm not 100% certain
that these were products

00:38:47.800 --> 00:38:51.770
of Cornelius's working style
or products of, you know,

00:38:51.770 --> 00:38:54.070
a brush being applied to
this daguerreotype plate

00:38:54.070 --> 00:38:56.680
when it was cleaned in the 1970s.

00:38:56.680 --> 00:39:03.030
But just to give you an indication
of how easily these can be abraded,

00:39:03.030 --> 00:39:05.830
you can see it really
makes a bunch of scratches

00:39:05.830 --> 00:39:09.020
on the surface which
cannot be removed.

00:39:09.020 --> 00:39:15.590
But to make matters worse for
this poor portrait of Goddard,

00:39:15.590 --> 00:39:18.690
I looked at it under
ultraviolet illumination

00:39:18.690 --> 00:39:21.700
and this one also has
cyanide all over the surface.

00:39:21.700 --> 00:39:25.490
So, it's likely-- it could
have been cleaned twice

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:28.760
with two different cleaners,
which isn't an uncommon phenomenon

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:30.880
for early daguerreotypes.

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:37.770
And the portrait of
Pierre Etienne DuPonceau,

00:39:37.770 --> 00:39:41.400
he survived a little
bit better than Goddard,

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:45.040 position:56%
so his plate on specular
illumination just shows a little bit

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:46.340
of the hazing.

00:39:46.340 --> 00:39:51.770
But what I wanted to point out here
is there are some distinct little

00:39:51.770 --> 00:39:56.770
polish marks on the plate, which
we looked at and saw on a lot

00:39:56.770 --> 00:39:59.050
of early daguerreotype plates.

00:39:59.050 --> 00:40:02.370
And we're thinking that maybe
at first these were significant

00:40:02.370 --> 00:40:05.850
in particular to Robert Cornelius
but we're finding on a lot

00:40:05.850 --> 00:40:10.360
of these old plates
from 1839 that were hand

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:14.810
on that these little tiny hash
marks in them that these could be,

00:40:14.810 --> 00:40:20.200
you know, a good indicator for
authenticity of material later.

00:40:32.520 --> 00:40:34.150
So, conservation treatment

00:40:34.150 --> 00:40:37.580
of the daguerreotype is rather a
controversial topic in the field

00:40:37.580 --> 00:40:39.910
of photograph conservation.

00:40:39.910 --> 00:40:42.240
And while there have been
people restoring art works

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:45.010
since there have been art around,

00:40:45.010 --> 00:40:48.900
the field of photograph
conservation is really quite new.

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:52.880
So, it formed its infancy in the
1970s at the George Eastman--

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:54.510
what was George Eastman house,

00:40:54.510 --> 00:40:57.910
which is now George Eastman
museum in Rochester, New York.

00:40:57.910 --> 00:40:59.210
And a group of caretakers

00:40:59.210 --> 00:41:02.380
of photographs were
developing treatment protocols

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:05.140
and preservation standards
for daguerreotypes.

00:41:05.140 --> 00:41:09.530
And these people eventually served
as the folks who were mentors

00:41:09.530 --> 00:41:13.520 position:56%
and teachers in the art conservation
programs that developed here

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:16.380
in the United States in the 1970s.

00:41:16.380 --> 00:41:18.780
And it was with all of
these people's efforts

00:41:18.780 --> 00:41:23.570
that photograph conservation was
established as a career path.

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:26.110
So, in reaction to all
of these well-intentioned

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:29.460
but rampant cleaning of
daguerreotypes that sometimes ended

00:41:29.460 --> 00:41:33.560
in destruction or undesirable
effects for the daguerreotypes,

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:38.270 position:56%
these folks put a moratorium on
cleaning daguerreotypes in the 1980s

00:41:38.270 --> 00:41:41.850
until they could further
study this issue.

00:41:41.850 --> 00:41:45.580
Nowadays, conservators are washing
daguerreotypes with various methods

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:49.050
that we have deemed to
be safe and ethical.

00:41:49.050 --> 00:41:51.620
Though there are some photograph
conservators to this day

00:41:51.620 --> 00:41:54.630
who still will not
wash a daguerreotype.

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:59.480
But still we need to intervene
with some aqueous methods sometimes

00:41:59.480 --> 00:42:02.020
on daguerreotypes and we need

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:06.490
to understand their long term
effects including the modern day

00:42:06.490 --> 00:42:07.910
techniques that we use.

00:42:07.910 --> 00:42:12.430
But right now in our field, we
really don't have any protocols

00:42:12.430 --> 00:42:15.550
for reducing or reversing effects

00:42:15.550 --> 00:42:18.290
of the historic cleaners
on daguerreotypes.

00:42:18.290 --> 00:42:21.650
We don't have any information on
cleaning ungilded daguerreotypes

00:42:21.650 --> 00:42:25.450 position:56%
and we're not even 100% certain of
the longevity of our current methods

00:42:25.450 --> 00:42:27.830
of cleaning gilded daguerreotype.

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:30.960
Leaving us with the question--
I forgot to show you this.

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:35.020
This is before and
after cyanide cleaning.

00:42:35.020 --> 00:42:39.250
So, this is just a quick path
to show what can be removed

00:42:39.250 --> 00:42:42.440
with our modern day methods.

00:42:42.440 --> 00:42:46.500
So, we're left with
this question of,

00:42:46.500 --> 00:42:50.070
can a conservator wash
these early daguerreotypes

00:42:50.070 --> 00:42:52.600 position:56%
that have been suffering the effects

00:42:52.600 --> 00:42:59.000
of multiple historic cleanings
over the last 177 years?

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:05.480
So, of course, that-- the question
is not a very simple answer.

00:43:05.480 --> 00:43:09.040
And as conservators, we can't
just experiment with these rare

00:43:09.040 --> 00:43:13.100
and early daguerreotypes as we have
to follow strict codes of ethics

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:15.450
in our field to do no harm.

00:43:15.450 --> 00:43:17.850
And in order to reverse
what we've already done,

00:43:17.850 --> 00:43:22.070 position:56%
what's already been done, a thorough
conservation science-based research

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:24.710
project needs to be
conducted before any method

00:43:24.710 --> 00:43:28.060
of treatment could even be
considered to be attempted.

00:43:28.060 --> 00:43:32.390
So, we need to understand the
effects of these historic cleaners,

00:43:32.390 --> 00:43:36.140
we also need to know the effects
of our current cleaners and we need

00:43:36.140 --> 00:43:39.890
to understand how to reverse
these damaging effects in a way

00:43:39.890 --> 00:43:42.740
that it will be safe and
preserve these daguerreotypes

00:43:42.740 --> 00:43:45.380
for the long haul.

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:49.060
So, a study of such
would include mockups

00:43:49.060 --> 00:43:52.010
that closely replicate
the early working methods

00:43:52.010 --> 00:43:55.890
of the daguerreotypist that
were working in 1839 in order

00:43:55.890 --> 00:43:58.840
to see what approach works best.

00:43:58.840 --> 00:44:01.410
Then and only then
when positive outcomes

00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:03.350
and safe procedures can be devised

00:44:03.350 --> 00:44:05.690
from these experiments
could we even think

00:44:05.690 --> 00:44:08.770
about performing conservation
treatment on these early rare

00:44:08.770 --> 00:44:12.330
and valuable daguerreotypes.

00:44:12.330 --> 00:44:15.320
So, with a project
of this magnitude,

00:44:15.320 --> 00:44:18.060
a team of experts is needed.

00:44:18.060 --> 00:44:23.270
So, as I mentioned before, some
people are in the audience.

00:44:23.270 --> 00:44:26.390
Adrienne Lundgren is on the
left, she's my colleague

00:44:26.390 --> 00:44:27.970
that I initially contacted.

00:44:27.970 --> 00:44:30.570 position:56%
And so, Adrienne and I on the right,

00:44:30.570 --> 00:44:34.450
decided with her supervisor Angie
Rob [assumed spelling] who's also

00:44:34.450 --> 00:44:37.140
here at Library of
Congress to develop a team

00:44:37.140 --> 00:44:39.650
of people to work on this project.

00:44:39.650 --> 00:44:42.820
So, we need a scientist and
the person that we chose

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:47.130
for the project is Edward
Vicenzi who's at Smithsonian MCI.

00:44:47.130 --> 00:44:50.730
And he's worked with
daguerreotype projects in the past

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:54.460
with a man named Mike Robinson
who's in the bottom left.

00:44:54.460 --> 00:44:58.010
And Mike Robinson is a
modern day daguerreotypist.

00:44:58.010 --> 00:45:01.660
So, Mike is the person who is
making all of our test samples.

00:45:01.660 --> 00:45:04.540
But together, they have worked
on some research with Southworth

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:07.170
and Hawes that has been
recently published.

00:45:07.170 --> 00:45:10.840
So, they were likely two
candidates for working

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:15.760
on a daguerreotype project
with Adrienne and I.

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:17.740 position:56%
We also-- Part of the research team,

00:45:17.740 --> 00:45:21.740
we're looking at the curatorial
aspects of daguerreotypes

00:45:21.740 --> 00:45:25.000
and early daguerreotypists and
so we need a curatorial team

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.090
and the people that we have
are Beverly Brannan from--

00:45:28.090 --> 00:45:31.870
she's a curator here of
photography at Library of Congress.

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:35.900
Will Stapp who was former curator
at the American Portrait Gallery

00:45:35.900 --> 00:45:40.550
and he is the author of the one
and only book on Robert Cornelius.

00:45:40.550 --> 00:45:44.290
And then recently joining our team
is Sarah Weatherwax who's curator

00:45:44.290 --> 00:45:48.860
of Prints and Photographs at the
Library Company in Philadelphia

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:53.240
who holds a lot of daguerreotypes
by Robert Cornelius as well.

00:45:53.240 --> 00:45:59.370
So, these people will be helping us
with a grant project that's been--

00:45:59.370 --> 00:46:03.270
that's application
process is current.

00:46:03.270 --> 00:46:08.460
Hoping to get the grant to form
a database of focusing primarily

00:46:08.460 --> 00:46:12.650
on the-- all of the works of Robert
Cornelius but also including other

00:46:12.650 --> 00:46:17.070
of Cornelius's contemporaries from
1839 to 1841 that we're working

00:46:17.070 --> 00:46:21.480
on this ungilded era
of daguerreotyping.

00:46:21.480 --> 00:46:27.600
So those, we plan to look at every
one of those and study their--

00:46:27.600 --> 00:46:30.360
them from a science-base,
conservation-base

00:46:30.360 --> 00:46:34.480 position:56%
and a curatorial-base aspect and
make a database that would be useful

00:46:34.480 --> 00:46:37.190
for collecting information.

00:46:37.190 --> 00:46:40.010
How these early daguerreotypes,
you know, how they looked,

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:43.080
how they were constructed, how
they survived over the years.

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:46.160
What kind of environments they
were in that will be useful

00:46:46.160 --> 00:46:50.830
for later phases of our studies.

00:46:50.830 --> 00:46:55.140
So, later investigations of this
project beyond what we're looking

00:46:55.140 --> 00:46:58.240
at now of just how the
historic cleaners affect these

00:46:58.240 --> 00:47:00.230
daguerreotype plates.

00:47:00.230 --> 00:47:04.320
We'll include studies on protocols,
how to reduce the damaging effects

00:47:04.320 --> 00:47:09.270
of these historic cleaners and
also how to develop proper storage

00:47:09.270 --> 00:47:13.890
and housing on recommendations for
daguerreotypes so that, you know,

00:47:13.890 --> 00:47:15.860
they don't tarnish in the future.

00:47:15.860 --> 00:47:20.380
It is of my personal
opinion that doing nothing

00:47:20.380 --> 00:47:22.910
with these daguerreotypes
and just letting them tarnish

00:47:22.910 --> 00:47:25.410
until they're completely
black is, you know,

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:29.700
kind of just as doing a disservice
to the daguerreotypes as, you know,

00:47:29.700 --> 00:47:32.630
intervening with historic
cleaners or,

00:47:32.630 --> 00:47:35.210
you know, trying out new methods.

00:47:35.210 --> 00:47:38.720 position:56%
I mean, we need to figure out a
proper way to do it before we try it

00:47:38.720 --> 00:47:43.500
but I think we can't just let
them deteriorate into nothing.

00:47:43.500 --> 00:47:49.380
So, I personally would like
to see this team and pull all

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:53.390
of our collaborative resources,
our expertise and our knowledge,

00:47:53.390 --> 00:47:57.930
our understanding of daguerreotypes
together to preserve all these rare

00:47:57.930 --> 00:48:01.160
and valuable irreplaceable
daguerreotypes

00:48:01.160 --> 00:48:03.170
that are the earliest
photographic treasures

00:48:03.170 --> 00:48:05.980
that we have here in
the United States.

00:48:05.980 --> 00:48:14.810
And I would like to see them exist
in another 177 years and beyond.

00:48:14.810 --> 00:48:17.550
So, here's just an example
of some of the works

00:48:17.550 --> 00:48:22.890
of Robert Cornelius starting at the
upper left with his self portrait

00:48:22.890 --> 00:48:25.190
and moving to the bottom right

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:29.430
through the years you can see
how his photography progressed.

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:35.510
And this is a time lapse video so,
those of you who are not familiar

00:48:35.510 --> 00:48:40.660
with conservation, we
don't work really fast.

00:48:40.660 --> 00:48:43.170
So, until we can do
all this research,

00:48:43.170 --> 00:48:47.860
we will just seal these
daguerreotypes back up in a way

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:52.880
that we know to be best using
our standard procedures and wait

00:48:52.880 --> 00:48:54.460
for the outcome of the research.

00:48:54.460 --> 00:48:57.470
And hopefully, I will be
back along with my colleague,

00:48:57.470 --> 00:49:01.200
Adrienne Lundgren, in a few years
presenting some positive results

00:49:01.200 --> 00:49:03.750
from our collective research.

00:49:03.750 --> 00:49:10.020
So, photography is a fragile
miracle of science and I hope that,

00:49:10.020 --> 00:49:12.100
you know, it can leave
and we can leave--

00:49:12.100 --> 00:49:17.030
hope it leave an indelible
mark on generations to come.

00:49:17.030 --> 00:49:19.510
Thank you very much.

