00:49:27.640 --> 00:49:28.940
Any questions?

00:49:28.940 --> 00:49:31.010
&gt;&gt; I have a question.

00:49:31.010 --> 00:49:32.310
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: Sure.

00:49:32.310 --> 00:49:37.560
&gt;&gt; Really great topic and
very detailed in a good way.

00:49:37.560 --> 00:49:41.140
Assuming some people who are
watching this has daguerreotypes

00:49:41.140 --> 00:49:42.900
at home or in their
family collections

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:46.960
and then perhaps they may want
to donate them to the Library

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:51.680
of Congress in the future, it may
happen, what would you suggest

00:49:51.680 --> 00:49:55.540
to them that they do
or not do to these?

00:49:55.540 --> 00:49:58.740
Like, I'm guessing, let's
say, can we wash them?

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:00.040
Control the humidity?

00:50:00.040 --> 00:50:01.340
What else would you say?

00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:02.640
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: Sure.

00:50:02.640 --> 00:50:05.630
So, the question for
the web audience was,

00:50:05.630 --> 00:50:08.480
if you have daguerreotypes
at home, what should you

00:50:08.480 --> 00:50:13.330
or should you not do while you
have them in your possession.

00:50:13.330 --> 00:50:17.820
So, unfortunately daguerreotypes
are these things that people are

00:50:17.820 --> 00:50:21.120
so curious about and they
love to pull out of the cases

00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:24.520
and open them up, but really,
you should just leave them alone.

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:28.870
People always think that there's
going to be a note or a patch

00:50:28.870 --> 00:50:30.810
of hair underneath the
daguerreotype and the case.

00:50:30.810 --> 00:50:33.090
But even just the action of
pulling the daguerreotypes

00:50:33.090 --> 00:50:36.570
out of the case can cause
damage to the daguerreotype.

00:50:36.570 --> 00:50:39.580
And if you're taking off
brass mats and preservers

00:50:39.580 --> 00:50:42.220
and disrupting things,
you're just opening things

00:50:42.220 --> 00:50:43.520
up to the environment.

00:50:43.520 --> 00:50:46.970
So, they were putting
these cases for a reason.

00:50:46.970 --> 00:50:51.850
So, the daguerreotypes, you should
keep them like most photographs.

00:50:51.850 --> 00:50:55.550
Not in your basement
and not in your attic.

00:50:55.550 --> 00:50:58.260
Daguerreotypes are usually
in the American style case,

00:50:58.260 --> 00:51:00.640
so they are sort of protected
from light themselves.

00:51:00.640 --> 00:51:03.370
But you, you know, might want to
keep them in an area of your house

00:51:03.370 --> 00:51:07.290
that isn't near the light or
is, you know, isn't exposed.

00:51:07.290 --> 00:51:09.780
It's not going to get exposed
through the leather case.

00:51:09.780 --> 00:51:12.770
But, in general, for
photographs, we tell people

00:51:12.770 --> 00:51:14.910
to keep them in the dark.

00:51:14.910 --> 00:51:16.330
But yeah, I think, just--

00:51:16.330 --> 00:51:19.430
like leaving them alone is
probably the best thing you can do,

00:51:19.430 --> 00:51:20.730
if that helps.

00:51:20.730 --> 00:51:23.500
&gt;&gt; Can you add storage to that?

00:51:23.500 --> 00:51:26.360
Storage conditions like what kind
of box we should put them in?

00:51:26.360 --> 00:51:27.660
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: OK.

00:51:27.660 --> 00:51:28.960
The question is in what kind

00:51:28.960 --> 00:51:30.260
of boxes should you
put daguerreotypes in?

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:34.670
Any kind of archival
base box that is made

00:51:34.670 --> 00:51:40.110 position:56%
from alkaline non-reactive materials
is fine to put the daguerreotype in.

00:51:40.110 --> 00:51:43.250
You can buy these readily
from archival suppliers.

00:51:43.250 --> 00:51:46.170
You can make your own
four flat boxes.

00:51:46.170 --> 00:51:49.080
There are instructions you can
find on the internet to do this.

00:51:49.080 --> 00:51:51.990
But just anything that's
non-reactive.

00:51:51.990 --> 00:51:54.290
Yes?

00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:58.510
&gt;&gt; Where are you in your research?

00:51:58.510 --> 00:52:00.220
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: The question
is where are we in the research.

00:52:00.220 --> 00:52:03.640
So, I'm actually here this week,
we're here on the research.

00:52:03.640 --> 00:52:06.810
We have already made the plate,
so we're just in the process

00:52:06.810 --> 00:52:10.400
of doing preliminary
testing, ACM testing.

00:52:10.400 --> 00:52:12.790
So, it's pretty early on.

00:52:12.790 --> 00:52:16.510
In the back.

00:52:16.510 --> 00:52:27.510
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:52:27.510 --> 00:52:31.400
Sure. The question was about
how do we limit the exposure

00:52:31.400 --> 00:52:36.330
of the ultraviolet illumination
when examining the photographs.

00:52:36.330 --> 00:52:42.090
So, I just-- thankfully, for the
power of digital photography today,

00:52:42.090 --> 00:52:44.430
it's-- you don't have to
expose it for very long.

00:52:44.430 --> 00:52:46.970
So, really, in just
turning on the light

00:52:46.970 --> 00:52:49.980
and then my photographers
clicking the camera

00:52:49.980 --> 00:52:53.570
and a few seconds later,
we have an image.

00:52:53.570 --> 00:52:57.190
So, it doesn't get that much
light exposure to the ultraviolet.

00:52:57.190 --> 00:53:00.140
&gt;&gt; Just keeping it low.

00:53:00.140 --> 00:53:02.330
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: Well, it had--
there's no like keeping it low,

00:53:02.330 --> 00:53:06.080
it's just one setting of UVC but--

00:53:06.080 --> 00:53:10.070
and a lot of people ask
me about light exposure

00:53:10.070 --> 00:53:13.330
like scanning photographs, but
that tiny little light that you get

00:53:13.330 --> 00:53:15.980
to take a photograph is
not going to be damaging.

00:53:15.980 --> 00:53:19.380
It's a cumulative light that causes
the damage to the photographs.

00:53:19.380 --> 00:53:25.400
I can't tell if that's
a question or not.

00:53:25.400 --> 00:53:26.700
Any other questions?

00:53:26.700 --> 00:53:28.000
In the back?

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:30.510
&gt;&gt; I just want to say thank
you for the presentation.

00:53:30.510 --> 00:53:47.270
