00:53:52.940 --> 00:53:56.500
Any other-- are there
web questions or-- Mary?

00:53:56.500 --> 00:53:57.800
OK.

00:53:57.800 --> 00:53:59.870
&gt;&gt; Mary: Well, yeah, I just
want to clarify, I'm sorry.

00:53:59.870 --> 00:54:06.470
If you do treat a daguerreotype,
do you throw out the old case?

00:54:06.470 --> 00:54:07.960
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel:
So, the question is,

00:54:07.960 --> 00:54:10.730
if I treated the daguerreotype,
do I throw out the old case?

00:54:10.730 --> 00:54:13.480
And the answer is no, we
don't throw out anything.

00:54:13.480 --> 00:54:16.930
Every once in a while a glass
is so deteriorated that we have

00:54:16.930 --> 00:54:18.450
to replace it with another glass.

00:54:18.450 --> 00:54:23.710 position:56%
But even in that case, I
personally return the original glass

00:54:23.710 --> 00:54:26.520
to the client and keep
the original materials

00:54:26.520 --> 00:54:30.540
with the object including the fact
that I've removed paper tape seals,

00:54:30.540 --> 00:54:32.790
I will take those paper
tape seals off,

00:54:32.790 --> 00:54:34.640
line them with a good
quality Japanese paper

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:36.250
and put them back on
the daguerreotype.

00:54:36.250 --> 00:54:40.330
So, yeah, I don't throw up anything
that is on the daguerreotype.

00:54:40.330 --> 00:54:43.830
&gt;&gt; Could you just continue on
with that and talk a little bit

00:54:43.830 --> 00:54:47.600
about attribution based on-- not
like how you would, say, the case

00:54:47.600 --> 00:54:53.490
or all those things in the light
of attribution for [inaudible].

00:54:53.490 --> 00:54:54.790
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: Yeah sure.

00:54:54.790 --> 00:55:00.090
So, in a case of the Cornelius's,
Cornelius made very specific cases

00:55:00.090 --> 00:55:04.430
and these are attributes
to his particular workings.

00:55:04.430 --> 00:55:07.840
So, for example, the self portrait,

00:55:07.840 --> 00:55:10.320
we do not have the original
case that it was in.

00:55:10.320 --> 00:55:11.900
So, this is problematic.

00:55:11.900 --> 00:55:13.340
So, this is another
reason why you don't want

00:55:13.340 --> 00:55:15.020
to take your daguerreotypes apart.

00:55:15.020 --> 00:55:17.650
Because some of these
materials are specific

00:55:17.650 --> 00:55:21.460
to the photographer's
working style himself

00:55:21.460 --> 00:55:26.140 position:56%
and can give us valuable information
that helps determine what kind

00:55:26.140 --> 00:55:29.480
of construction or working
methodology one conservator--

00:55:29.480 --> 00:55:32.130
or I'm sorry, one photographer had.

00:55:32.130 --> 00:55:36.230
And it will help us study a
broad collection of materials.

00:55:36.230 --> 00:55:40.580
So, by, you know-- and it's a
pretty common practice in sort

00:55:40.580 --> 00:55:43.550
of dealing industry to
take a daguerreotype

00:55:43.550 --> 00:55:45.800
out of one case and
put it in another.

00:55:45.800 --> 00:55:47.170
But even-- there are, you know,

00:55:47.170 --> 00:55:49.150
daguerreotype photography
became very popular

00:55:49.150 --> 00:55:51.400
and there were quite a few
people making portraits

00:55:51.400 --> 00:55:53.920
by the, you know, 1850s.

00:55:53.920 --> 00:55:56.800
But some of the earlier
things really need to remain

00:55:56.800 --> 00:56:00.050
in these materials that they
were placed in originally

00:56:00.050 --> 00:56:03.320
because they do provide a
lot of valuable information.

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:08.160
And so, we can also tell a
lot of why things deteriorate

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:11.390
in a certain way based on
the materials that they used.

00:56:11.390 --> 00:56:15.250
So, if you switch out a case and
we don't have the original case,

00:56:15.250 --> 00:56:17.930
we don't know how that
material reacted

00:56:17.930 --> 00:56:23.300
with the photograph over a time.

00:56:23.300 --> 00:56:25.050
Yes?

00:56:25.050 --> 00:56:38.140
&gt;&gt; Let me ask you, do you
know at the time in the 1840,

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:42.550
'50s how expensive
it would have been

00:56:42.550 --> 00:56:45.820 position:56%
to take a portrait of daguerreotype?

00:56:45.820 --> 00:56:47.120
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: OK.

00:56:47.120 --> 00:56:48.950 position:56%
The question is how expensive it was

00:56:48.950 --> 00:56:51.530
to have your daguerreotype
portrait made.

00:56:51.530 --> 00:56:57.130
As I mentioned, we don't have
any Robert Cornelius's notes,

00:56:58.650 --> 00:57:07.000
but there's a lot of advertisements
from the early 19th century

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:09.540
from daguerreotype studios.

00:57:09.540 --> 00:57:14.950
So, it was roughly $5 to have a
daguerreotype made, which was a lot

00:57:14.950 --> 00:57:20.990
of money in 1830s, 1840s.

00:57:20.990 --> 00:57:22.590
Any other questions?

00:57:22.590 --> 00:57:24.450
&gt;&gt; What do you consider

00:57:24.450 --> 00:57:28.060
to be appropriate housing
for loose plates?

00:57:28.060 --> 00:57:30.610
&gt;&gt; Rachel K. Wetzel: The
question is what do I consider

00:57:30.610 --> 00:57:33.880
to be appropriate housing
for loose plates?

00:57:33.880 --> 00:57:36.740
Well, loose plates are
extremely problematic

00:57:36.740 --> 00:57:40.450
because they're 100%
exposed to the environment.

00:57:40.450 --> 00:57:43.130
So, there were famous
daguerreotypist plate

00:57:43.130 --> 00:57:48.010
that were found in these
wooden boxes that they used

00:57:48.010 --> 00:57:50.800
in the 19th century to store
their box-- their daguerreotypes.

00:57:50.800 --> 00:57:55.470
But, you know, have
faired OK but in general,

00:57:55.470 --> 00:57:58.160
we don't recommend any wood.

00:57:58.160 --> 00:58:03.260
But I would definitely recommend
having a conservator seal

00:58:03.260 --> 00:58:07.540
up your daguerreotype in
a very simple package just

00:58:07.540 --> 00:58:10.100
so it isn't exposed
to the environment.

00:58:10.100 --> 00:58:13.850
So, one-- in part of
this Cornelius project,

00:58:13.850 --> 00:58:17.460
I have met with family
members of Robert Cornelius

00:58:17.460 --> 00:58:21.450
who have some portraits
of family members.

00:58:21.450 --> 00:58:27.020 position:56%
And the one portrait that Al showed
to me, he handed me was a bare plate

00:58:27.020 --> 00:58:29.420
and there was no image on it.

00:58:30.990 --> 00:58:34.840
He just stuck it in my hand
and he was like, turn it over.

00:58:34.840 --> 00:58:37.350
And I turned it over and
there's an etch on the back

00:58:37.350 --> 00:58:40.100
that says portrait
by Robert Cornelius.

00:58:40.100 --> 00:58:41.710
I'm like, why is this
in my bare hand?

00:58:41.710 --> 00:58:44.560
So, you leave it out and
it tarnishes to, you know,

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:45.860
the images are 100% obscured.

00:58:45.860 --> 00:58:47.160
So, you know, these plates,

00:58:47.160 --> 00:58:48.460
particularly this one
really needed a housing.

00:58:48.460 --> 00:58:49.760
So, conservator is the
way to go for that.

00:58:49.760 --> 00:58:51.060
&gt;&gt; What was the wash bath
in the washing video?

